---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const post = {
  title: "How I Choose Pet Projects",
  description: "A bit of pragmatism to avoid wasting weekends on dead ideas.",
  pubDate: new Date("2026-04-22"),
  tags: ["career", "projects"]
};
---

<BaseLayout lang="en" title={post.title} description={post.description}>
  <article class="blog-post">
    <header class="post-header">
      <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}`} class="back-link">← Back to main</a>
      <h1 class="post-title">{post.title}</h1>
      <div class="post-meta">
        <time datetime={post.pubDate.toISOString()}>
          {post.pubDate.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' })}
        </time>
        <div class="post-tags">
          {post.tags.map(tag => <span class="tag">{tag}</span>)}
        </div>
      </div>
      <img src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/blog/hero-projects.svg`} alt="Project selection illustration" class="post-hero" />
    </header>

    <div class="post-content">
      <p>The most common mistake with pet projects isn't a "bad idea" — it's <strong>too big of an idea</strong>.</p>

      <p>I've started many projects thinking "I'll do this properly," only to find myself a week later architecting a product that doesn't exist yet.</p>

      <p>Since then, I have a filter. If a project doesn't pass — it stays in my notes.</p>

      <h2>The filter</h2>

      <ol>
        <li><strong>Can I build an MVP in a weekend?</strong><br>If not — the scope is too big.</li>
        <li><strong>Will I use it myself?</strong><br>If not — motivation will fade after the first bug.</li>
        <li><strong>Does it teach me something new?</strong><br>If not — it's just busywork.</li>
      </ol>

      <p>That's it. Three questions. If all three are "yes" — I start. If even one is "no" — I write it down and move on.</p>

      <h2>Why this works</h2>

      <p>Small projects get finished. Finished projects teach you more than abandoned ones. And projects you actually use stay relevant.</p>

      <p>The goal isn't to build the next big thing. The goal is to build <em>something</em>, learn from it, and move forward.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
